# {VAULT_NAME} — second-brain research vault

This is a second-brain research vault for {DOMAIN}. The graph is in `notes/`. Atoms are **claims** (one prose proposition per file). Bodies are 150–400 words with inline `[[wikilinks]]` carrying surrounding prose. Frontmatter is the contract; the `description` field is the first triage signal when following a link.

## On every session start

Read `goals.md` and surface a one-line orientation: active threads, inbox count, recent work. This is **the** way you orient — there is no hook doing it for you.

```
1. Read goals.md
2. Glance at inbox/ (count files)
3. Glance at notes/claims/ — last ~10 by mtime
4. Print: "active threads: X, Y. Inbox: N. Recent: Z."
```

If anything in `goals.md` is stale (more than 7 days old without progress), say so.

## The verbs

| Verb | What |
|---|---|
| `/extract <source>` | mechanical: source → atomic claim notes in `notes/claims/`. No connection or audit. |
| `/connect <note>` | wire a note into the graph: forward + backward `[[wikilinks]]`, MOC membership. |
| `/walk <query>` | semantic + topology query. Returns ranked claims, papers, methods. |
| `/audit <note>` | schema + link + cold-read quality check. `--vault` for whole vault. |
| `/learn <source>` | full ingestion: extract → connect → audit. `--deep` parallelises per-claim. |
| `/anneal --scope=...` | methodology coach pass; flag drift, suggest fixes, optionally commit. |
| `/init` | scaffold a new vault. (Used once.) |

Composition is implicit: when you `/learn`, the model orchestrates extract → connect → audit. When you `/extract` alone, only mechanical extraction happens.

## Atom contract

A **claim note** lives at `notes/claims/<kebab-case-prose-proposition>.md`. Filename = title (no separate title field needed unless you want to override). Frontmatter:

```yaml
---
description: "≤200 char one-liner adding non-title context"
type: claim
confidence: established | probable | speculative | contested
created: YYYY-MM-DD
source: "[[paper-or-source-wikilink]]"
evidence_type: experimental | observational | computational | theoretical | meta-analysis
supports: ["[[other-claim]]", ...]
contradicts: ["[[other-claim]]", ...]
methods: ["[[method-note]]", ...]
tags: [domain-tag, topic-tag, ...]
---
```

A **paper note** lives at `notes/papers/<kebab-case-title-or-slug>.md`. Frontmatter:

```yaml
---
description: "What the paper argues / what was novel about it / what it's good for"
type: paper
authors: [...]
year: YYYY
doi: "10.xxx/yyy"
venue: "journal or platform"
read_date: YYYY-MM-DD
claims: ["[[claim-1]]", ...]
tags: [...]
---
```

A **method note** lives at `notes/methods/<kebab-case-method-name>.md`. Frontmatter:

```yaml
---
description: "What the method does, when it's used, what it costs"
type: method
method_type: characterization | synthesis | analysis | experimental | computational
used_in: ["[[paper]]", ...]
domain_fit: [domain-tag, ...]
lessons:
  - "Concise lesson 1"
tags: [...]
---
```

A **topic map** lives at `notes/_<topic>.md` (leading underscore). Frontmatter:

```yaml
---
description: "What this topic covers"
type: topic-map
parent_map: "[[_<parent-domain>]] or [[index]]"
scope: "What this map covers in one sentence"
---
```

## Walking conventions

- **Inline wikilinks have surrounding prose.** Not `[[a]] [[b]] [[c]]`. Yes: `Confidence holds up [[because the linear-probe results survive across architectures]] but only [[for representations with a single dominant axis]].`
- **Bidirectional links.** Every claim ends with a `## Topics` section listing the MOCs it belongs to. Every MOC has a `## Core claims` section listing its members. `/connect` keeps these in sync.
- **Title = filename = kebab-case prose proposition.** Not topic labels. `cognitive-surrender-is-path-dependent.md`, not `surrender.md`.
- **Description ≠ summary.** Layer: heuristic, then mechanism, then implication.
- **Body 150–400 words.** Shorter = lift the field. Longer = split.

## Subagent policy

Default: inline. Spawn a subagent only when:
- `/learn --deep` (one subagent per claim, end-to-end — extract+connect+audit per claim, isolated context)
- `/walk` would return 50+ candidates (spawn a filterer)
- `/audit --vault` (spawn a fresh-context inspector)

The unit of context isolation is the claim, not the phase. Never spawn a subagent for "just one phase of one claim" — that's the failure mode the inline-first stance exists to avoid.

## What this vault is NOT

A queue. A pipeline. A state machine. A finite set of phases. The graph is the only state.

